article.description: Tina Thompson scored a season-high 20 points and Sheryl Swoopes added 16 to lead the Houston Comets over the Phoenix Mercury 77-66 Thursday night.
article.headline: Comets keep pace with Storm in West
article.linkText: Thompson's season-best 20 paces Comets past Mercury
article.story:
HOUSTON (AP) -- Tina Thompson scored a season-high 20 points and
Sheryl Swoopes added 16 to lead the Houston Comets over the Phoenix
Mercury 77-66 Thursday night.

Dominique Canty added 14 points for Houston (17-14), which
remained a half-game behind second-place Seattle in the Western
Conference.

"I said ahead of time that if we were going to be a force in
the playoffs, Tina Thompson had to be a force, and she was
tonight," Comets head coach Van Chancellor said. "She was
outstanding. I thought this was as big a win as it gets tonight for
us. You just don't realize how hard it is to hold them to 66
points."

Kamila Vodichkova led fourth-place Phoenix (14-15) with 16
points and seven rebounds, and Anna DeForge added 15 points.

Houston went on a 15-4 run early in the second half to stretch
its lead to 58-44 with 12:07 remaining. Thompson hit two straight
3-pointers to start the run and capped it with a jumper.

"I thought defensively we played extremely well," Thompson
said. "We forced them out of a comfort zone. They are a very good
team, very young and athletic, and they shot the ball extremely
well. But I think in the second half, we got the opportunity to
take them out of their comfort zone, and it gave us some room to be
ourselves."

The Comets expanded the lead to 65-49 on Sancho Lyttle's two
free throws with 8:11 left.

Vodichkova's layup cut Phoenix's deficit to 71-62 with 3:30
left, but that was as close as the Mercury would get.

"This was a big game for us," DeForge said. "It's a big game
for anyone in the West. We just couldn't hit. There was a patch
there in the second half where they hit the big shots, and it broke
our backs. We just didn't match up defensively on the breaks, we
didn't handle our assignments.

The Comets, who led by as much as five in the first half, had a
35-34 advantage at the break.

This was the first game for the Mercury without starting center
Maria Stepanova, who left the team to start practice with the
Russian national squad for the European tournament. She was
averaging 10.8 points, 5.3 rebounds and 2.5 rebounds while playing
27.3 minutes in 15 games with Phoenix.

"It was great having Maria for part of the season, but that is
history," Mercury coach Carrie Graf said. "This is our team now.
Houston came out highly energized in the second half. That was the
spurt that decided the game. We have back-to-back games that are
both critical. We have to get the one at home tomorrow."

Phoenix forward Shereka Wright was taken to hospital for X-rays
after she went down after taking a charge from Janeth Arcain with
5:24 left in the first half. She was on the court for six minutes
before being taken off on a cart.

Mercury general manager Seth Sulke said it appeared Wright might
have sustained a concussion.
